    id: 'ch19-s7',
    heading: 'Education, Accessibility, and Humanitarian AI',
    body: 'ML-powered educational tools can personalize learning experiences, provide intelligent tutoring, automate assessment, and make education more accessible to underserved populations. Adaptive learning systems adjust content difficulty and sequencing based on individual student performance, providing each learner with an optimized path through the material.\n\nAccessibility applications use ML to break down barriers for people with disabilities. Speech recognition enables voice-controlled interfaces. Computer vision powers image description for the visually impaired. Sign language recognition bridges communication gaps. Real-time translation and captioning make content accessible across languages and hearing abilities.\n\nHumanitarian applications of ML address urgent needs in disaster response, poverty alleviation, food security, and conflict prevention. ML systems can process satellite imagery to assess disaster damage, predict food insecurity from economic and environmental indicators, and optimize resource allocation for humanitarian organizations.\n\nDeploying ML in education and humanitarian settings requires special attention to equity, privacy, and developmental appropriateness. Systems must work equally well for diverse populations and not reinforce existing inequities. Student data privacy and protection of vulnerable populations are essential considerations.',
